1
00:00:15,098 --> 00:00:18,090
[WOMAN SINGING
"ES IST EIN ROS ENTSPRUNGEN"]

2
00:00:48,832 --> 00:00:50,823
[BOTH SINGING]

3
00:01:01,177 --> 00:01:02,735
I can't sing.

4
00:01:02,912 --> 00:01:04,504
ANNETTE:
That was fine, Henry.

5
00:01:04,681 --> 00:01:05,909
HENRY:
I can't sing like you.

6
00:01:06,583 --> 00:01:09,074
Of course not.
You're supposed to sing like you.

7
00:01:09,252 --> 00:01:12,050
Dad says I can't carry a tune
in a wheelbarrow.

8
00:01:12,222 --> 00:01:13,519
ANNETTE:
Dad was joking.

9
00:01:13,690 --> 00:01:16,181
I love your voice.
We both love your voice.

10
00:01:16,359 --> 00:01:18,350
[BELL RINGING]

11
00:01:20,697 --> 00:01:24,565
How about "Jingle Bells"?
That you can sing.

12
00:01:25,902 --> 00:01:28,894
[BOTH SINGING "JINGLE BELLS"]

13
00:01:40,016 --> 00:01:41,415
[TIRES SQUEAL]

14
00:01:48,792 --> 00:01:50,089
Mommy!

15
00:01:51,561 --> 00:01:53,051
Henry.

16
00:01:57,901 --> 00:01:59,630
ANNETTE:
"...for the third time and said:

17
00:01:59,803 --> 00:02:03,239
'What will you give me
if I spin the straw for you this time also? '

18
00:02:03,406 --> 00:02:07,342
'I have nothing left that I could give,'
answered the girl.

19
00:02:07,744 --> 00:02:12,181
'Then promise me, if you should
become queen, your first child.'

20
00:02:12,348 --> 00:02:16,478
'Who knows whether that will ever happen? '
Thought the miller's daughter."

21
00:02:18,154 --> 00:02:20,145
[PANTING]

22
00:02:22,926 --> 00:02:24,917
[TIRES SQUEALING]

23
00:02:27,430 --> 00:02:30,228
- No! Mommy!
- Henry. Henry.

24
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:32,732
- There's nothing you can do. No. Shh.
- Let me go! Mommy!

25
00:02:32,902 --> 00:02:35,166
There's nothing you can do.
Listen. Listen to me.

26
00:02:35,338 --> 00:02:36,669
I don't have much time.

27
00:02:36,840 --> 00:02:39,604
You were in the car. It was spinning.
And all of a sudden...

28
00:02:39,776 --> 00:02:41,767
...you were home
and it was two weeks ago...

29
00:02:41,945 --> 00:02:46,541
...and you were watching yourself.
Watching your mom and dad read to you.

30
00:02:47,684 --> 00:02:51,620
You time-traveled, okay?
Just like I did to come to see you.

31
00:02:51,788 --> 00:02:55,781
I'm you, Henry. Understand?
When you're grown up.

32
00:02:55,959 --> 00:02:58,086
We're the same person.

33
00:02:58,461 --> 00:03:01,089
I know that's hard to understand,
but you will someday.

34
00:03:01,264 --> 00:03:03,255
WOMAN:
Oh, my God.

35
00:03:03,666 --> 00:03:04,690
I have to go now.

36
00:03:05,835 --> 00:03:10,101
But you don't need to be afraid, Henry.
You're gonna be okay, I promise.

37
00:03:16,613 --> 00:03:18,911
WOMAN:
Help that little boy!

38
00:03:19,082 --> 00:03:20,106
[CLOTHING CRUMPLES]

39
00:04:21,377 --> 00:04:24,608
- That took you long enough.
- You have no idea.

40
00:04:24,881 --> 00:04:26,075
Okay.

41
00:04:26,249 --> 00:04:28,979
So Christmas Eve. Got any plans?

42
00:04:29,152 --> 00:04:30,744
Yeah, yeah. Big plans.

43
00:04:32,889 --> 00:04:35,119
WAITRESS: Anything else?
- No, thank you.

44
00:04:41,397 --> 00:04:45,094
Merry Christmas. Thank you very much.

45
00:05:11,060 --> 00:05:13,961
MAN [ON RADIO]: Good morning, Chicago.
ChiTown radio time is 8 a.m.

46
00:05:14,130 --> 00:05:15,927
News and sports are coming up next.

47
00:05:16,099 --> 00:05:19,159
Shaping up to be a warm first day of spring
here in the Windy City.

48
00:05:24,474 --> 00:05:28,740
Excuse me. I'm looking for something
on papermaking at Kelmscott.

49
00:05:28,911 --> 00:05:31,971
Our special-collections librarian
can help you with that.

50
00:05:34,017 --> 00:05:35,314
Can I help you?

51
00:05:39,889 --> 00:05:41,481
Henry?

52
00:05:43,326 --> 00:05:44,691
Yes?

53
00:05:50,633 --> 00:05:52,294
Henry.

54
00:05:52,769 --> 00:05:54,100
It's you.

55
00:05:56,339 --> 00:05:59,001
You told me this would happen.

56
00:05:59,208 --> 00:06:03,338
I'm supposed to act normal,
but I'm not really acting very normal.

57
00:06:09,052 --> 00:06:13,250
I'm sorry.
I really have no idea who you are.

58
00:06:14,757 --> 00:06:15,985
I'm Clare.

59
00:06:16,526 --> 00:06:18,494
Clare Abshire.

60
00:06:19,128 --> 00:06:21,961
Now, I know...
I know you don't know me.

61
00:06:23,433 --> 00:06:27,665
Look, I know how odd this must be for you.
It's odd for me.

62
00:06:27,837 --> 00:06:29,634
But, um...

63
00:06:30,740 --> 00:06:34,699
...would you like to have dinner with me,
and I'll explain?

64
00:06:36,312 --> 00:06:39,713
Henry, we've been planning this dinner
for a long time.

65
00:06:41,117 --> 00:06:42,482
We have?

66
00:06:43,786 --> 00:06:47,187
Go to the Beau Thai. It's your favorite.

67
00:06:48,324 --> 00:06:50,417
- It is.
- Mm-hm.

68
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:59,499
You look like you've been
having a hard time.

69
00:07:02,538 --> 00:07:05,166
You know, everything's gonna be okay.

70
00:07:09,445 --> 00:07:14,041
So, um, is it "yes," then, to dinner?

71
00:07:15,685 --> 00:07:17,516
Okay.

72
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:20,186
Okay.

73
00:07:22,658 --> 00:07:23,852
- Okay.
- Yeah.

74
00:07:24,026 --> 00:07:25,687
Yeah. Um...

75
00:07:26,195 --> 00:07:28,686
- So Beau Thai, 7.
HENRY: Mm-hm.

76
00:07:28,865 --> 00:07:30,696
See you there.

77
00:07:31,234 --> 00:07:32,565
[LAUGHS]

78
00:07:35,304 --> 00:07:36,532
[SIGHS]

79
00:07:57,527 --> 00:07:59,085
Oh, shit.

80
00:08:17,380 --> 00:08:18,711
[GRUNTS]

81
00:08:35,698 --> 00:08:37,495
COP 1: Hey.
HENRY: Oh, man.

82
00:08:37,667 --> 00:08:38,964
Going somewhere, asshole?

83
00:08:39,135 --> 00:08:40,500
I wouldn't bother.

84
00:08:40,670 --> 00:08:41,967
Yeah? Why's that?

85
00:08:42,138 --> 00:08:43,162
[GRUNTS]

86
00:08:43,339 --> 00:08:45,671
- You'll see.
COP 2: Shut up.

87
00:08:55,384 --> 00:08:58,046
- Dispatch, Unit 11.
DISPATCHER [OVER RADIO]: Go ahead, 11.

88
00:08:58,221 --> 00:08:59,813
I got a...

89
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:05,025
Jesus Christ.

90
00:09:07,697 --> 00:09:11,861
WAITER: Would you like another glass?
- Sure. Thank you.

91
00:09:14,203 --> 00:09:16,694
Sorry. I was, uh, detained.

92
00:09:17,607 --> 00:09:20,269
- Are you okay?
- Yeah, no big deal.

93
00:09:22,011 --> 00:09:23,308
Thank you.

94
00:09:23,479 --> 00:09:26,380
You do understand
why it is I don't know you?

95
00:09:26,916 --> 00:09:29,180
Uh, of course.

96
00:09:29,352 --> 00:09:32,515
When you're older,
you'll travel back to when I'm a little girl.

97
00:09:32,688 --> 00:09:34,280
For me, ahh...

98
00:09:34,457 --> 00:09:37,893
I mean, I've known you since...
Since I was 6 years old.

99
00:09:38,494 --> 00:09:41,327
Since, um, you appeared in the meadow
behind my parents' house...

100
00:09:41,497 --> 00:09:43,226
...where I used to play.

101
00:09:43,399 --> 00:09:45,060
Um...

102
00:09:46,135 --> 00:09:48,330
You're not really supposed to drink.

103
00:09:49,205 --> 00:09:50,502
Why's that?

104
00:09:50,673 --> 00:09:54,404
Well, you told me that Dr. Kendrick said
that you should stop drinking...

105
00:09:54,577 --> 00:09:56,943
...because it makes you travel.

106
00:09:57,546 --> 00:10:00,845
- Who's Dr. Kendrick?
- He's your doctor.

107
00:10:01,484 --> 00:10:06,786
He wins the Berger for his work in genetics.
He... He helps you.

108
00:10:08,858 --> 00:10:10,257
This is too much.

109
00:10:11,727 --> 00:10:13,490
I'm sorry.

110
00:10:14,096 --> 00:10:17,361
You told me to go easy on you,
and, um, I'm not.

111
00:10:20,703 --> 00:10:22,034
Ahh...

112
00:10:25,541 --> 00:10:27,873
I wrote down every time
that you came to visit me.

113
00:10:28,811 --> 00:10:32,440
Which I gather I did, or will do,
fairly often.

114
00:10:32,915 --> 00:10:35,748
The last time that I saw you, I was 18.

115
00:10:35,951 --> 00:10:39,546
Seems that you go back
to the same places a lot.

116
00:10:39,722 --> 00:10:41,656
Yeah, it's like gravity.

117
00:10:41,824 --> 00:10:43,792
Big events pull you in.

118
00:10:45,661 --> 00:10:47,151
I was a big event.

119
00:10:48,064 --> 00:10:49,258
So it would seem.

120
00:10:59,809 --> 00:11:01,242
Clare, right?

121
00:11:03,145 --> 00:11:04,271
Yeah.

122
00:11:05,014 --> 00:11:09,007
Could we pretend just for a minute
that this is the first time we've met?

123
00:11:12,555 --> 00:11:14,250
Okay.

124
00:11:14,957 --> 00:11:16,424
Sure.

125
00:11:18,060 --> 00:11:19,960
It's just that...

126
00:11:20,129 --> 00:11:22,529
It's just that you're my best friend.

127
00:11:23,432 --> 00:11:26,595
I've been in love with you all my life.

128
00:11:29,939 --> 00:11:32,965
CLARE: Is this really necessary?
HENRY: Yeah. Count to 1000.

129
00:11:33,142 --> 00:11:34,507
CLARE:
Ahh...

130
00:11:34,677 --> 00:11:36,042
Okay.

131
00:11:36,979 --> 00:11:38,446
One.

132
00:11:39,415 --> 00:11:41,349
Two.

133
00:11:42,651 --> 00:11:44,482
Three.

134
00:11:45,554 --> 00:11:47,181
Four hundred.

135
00:11:47,356 --> 00:11:48,914
Six hundred.

136
00:11:49,592 --> 00:11:51,457
Eight hundred.

137
00:11:51,627 --> 00:11:53,424
A thousand.

138
00:12:04,073 --> 00:12:05,540
Do you want a drink?

139
00:12:16,085 --> 00:12:18,053
I don't want a drink.

140
00:12:43,379 --> 00:12:45,779
God, you're so young.

141
00:13:06,735 --> 00:13:08,362
HENRY:
Tell me again.

142
00:13:08,537 --> 00:13:10,471
How did we meet?

143
00:13:13,509 --> 00:13:16,000
You're older than you are now.

144
00:13:16,812 --> 00:13:19,576
Maybe I'm not supposed to tell you.

145
00:13:20,583 --> 00:13:22,244
Well, I think I need to know.

146
00:13:55,384 --> 00:13:56,715
[FOOTSTEPS IN FOREST]

147
00:13:59,054 --> 00:14:00,453
Who's there?

148
00:14:00,623 --> 00:14:02,318
HENRY:
Greetings, Earthling.

149
00:14:02,491 --> 00:14:05,358
Mark, you idiot.

150
00:14:08,130 --> 00:14:12,692
HENRY: Ow! Clare, I'm not gonna hurt you.
Just please don't throw anything at me.

151
00:14:12,868 --> 00:14:16,827
Who are you, how do you know my name,
and why can't you come out?

152
00:14:17,940 --> 00:14:20,204
HENRY:
Can you just hand me the blanket?

153
00:14:20,376 --> 00:14:21,809
Maybe I should call my mom.

154
00:14:21,977 --> 00:14:24,445
HENRY:
No, no, no. Don't call your mom, please.

155
00:14:24,613 --> 00:14:27,946
Just hand me the blanket and I'll leave.

156
00:14:42,097 --> 00:14:44,361
What do you need the blanket for?

157
00:14:44,533 --> 00:14:46,660
HENRY:
I'm a time traveler.

158
00:14:48,504 --> 00:14:50,802
I come from the future.

159
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:54,232
And when I do,
I don't get to bring my clothes.

160
00:14:54,843 --> 00:14:57,004
There's no such thing as time travelers.

161
00:14:57,446 --> 00:14:58,879
Yes, there is.

162
00:14:59,048 --> 00:15:02,745
In fact, you and I are friends
in the future.

163
00:15:03,218 --> 00:15:06,210
- When you're a lady.
- Am I pretty?

164
00:15:06,722 --> 00:15:08,314
Yes.

165
00:15:08,490 --> 00:15:10,321
Very.

166
00:15:10,693 --> 00:15:12,092
Prove you're from the future.

167
00:15:13,462 --> 00:15:16,454
Well, your name is Clare Abshire.

168
00:15:16,632 --> 00:15:19,362
Born May 24th, 1972.

169
00:15:19,535 --> 00:15:22,595
- Your parents are Philip and Lucille...
- So you know things.

170
00:15:22,771 --> 00:15:25,171
That doesn't prove
you're from the future.

171
00:15:25,341 --> 00:15:27,036
Okay.

172
00:15:28,544 --> 00:15:33,277
This weekend, your brother, Mark,
who's a real pain in the ass...

173
00:15:33,449 --> 00:15:35,440
...falls out of a tree and breaks his arm.

174
00:15:36,018 --> 00:15:40,114
Yeah, but I won't know till then
if you're telling the truth or not.

175
00:15:40,956 --> 00:15:44,551
Well, if you hang around long enough,
you'll see me disappear.

176
00:15:44,860 --> 00:15:46,794
But you just got here.

177
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:49,998
I'll be back again.

178
00:15:50,332 --> 00:15:52,266
Lots of times.

179
00:15:52,568 --> 00:15:54,365
In fact...

180
00:15:55,070 --> 00:15:58,870
...I'll be back next Tuesday at 4.

181
00:15:59,742 --> 00:16:03,803
And it'd be great if, when you come then,
you could bring me some clothes.

182
00:16:05,047 --> 00:16:07,242
Something your dad won't miss.

183
00:16:08,917 --> 00:16:10,578
Nice to meet you.

184
00:18:10,773 --> 00:18:14,675
Don't worry about that.
It's been over for a while.

185
00:18:18,547 --> 00:18:20,640
This is weird.

186
00:18:21,717 --> 00:18:25,915
I never knew you at this age.
I mean, I've only known you as this...

187
00:18:27,289 --> 00:18:29,120
...mature, worldly person.

188
00:18:29,691 --> 00:18:32,125
I'm competing against myself.

189
00:18:35,564 --> 00:18:37,293
No.

190
00:18:42,971 --> 00:18:45,940
You were just kind of my perfect guy.

191
00:18:53,048 --> 00:18:55,209
CLARE:
I just can't get used to this.

192
00:18:55,384 --> 00:18:57,852
I mean, I just keep waiting for you
to disappear.

193
00:18:58,020 --> 00:18:59,612
HENRY:
Oh, it'll happen, believe me.

194
00:19:01,557 --> 00:19:03,388
How's it feel?

195
00:19:03,559 --> 00:19:06,619
I mean, I know what it's like
to watch you go...

196
00:19:06,795 --> 00:19:10,287
...but what's it like
to always be the one that's going?

197
00:19:11,800 --> 00:19:16,464
Sometimes it feels like
you've stood up too quickly.

198
00:19:16,638 --> 00:19:21,473
Your hands and feet are tingling,
and then they're not there at all.

199
00:19:21,877 --> 00:19:25,608
Sometimes it feels like your attention
has wandered just for an instant...

200
00:19:26,348 --> 00:19:29,181
...then you're standing naked someplace.

201
00:19:29,351 --> 00:19:32,377
Maybe you've been there before,
maybe you haven't.

202
00:19:32,921 --> 00:19:35,913
You don't know how long it's gonna last,
so you start walking...

203
00:19:36,091 --> 00:19:37,490
...till you find some clothes.

204
00:19:38,093 --> 00:19:40,084
[CAR ALARM BLARING]

205
00:19:40,796 --> 00:19:42,991
Then you seem just like everybody else.

206
00:19:44,366 --> 00:19:47,893
Except you're stranded and all alone,
just waiting to disappear.

207
00:19:48,070 --> 00:19:50,197
CLARE:
But you get to see people from the past.

208
00:19:50,639 --> 00:19:53,164
People who are gone, like your mom.

209
00:19:53,609 --> 00:19:56,976
Yeah, but the thing is,
you can't change what happens to them.

210
00:19:57,145 --> 00:20:00,137
I've tried. It just happens anyway.

211
00:20:31,914 --> 00:20:34,610
HENRY: It's nice. Hey.
- And this is Charisse, my roommate.

212
00:20:34,783 --> 00:20:36,216
- Hi.
CLARE: My best friend.

213
00:20:36,385 --> 00:20:38,683
- And our excellent cook for tonight.
- Welcome.

214
00:20:38,854 --> 00:20:40,344
Because I don't cook.

215
00:20:40,522 --> 00:20:44,424
Well, you should know that going in.
She's a lovely girl, but she can't cook toast.

216
00:20:44,593 --> 00:20:46,584
- Gomez?
- Yeah, short for Gomolinski.

217
00:20:46,762 --> 00:20:48,730
It's really nice to meet you.

218
00:20:48,897 --> 00:20:52,765
We didn't wanna meet you, but seems to be
the only way to catch a glimpse of Clare.

219
00:20:52,935 --> 00:20:54,527
CHARISSE:
Please ignore Gomez.

220
00:20:54,703 --> 00:20:56,432
- Do you want some wine?
- No, thanks.

221
00:20:56,605 --> 00:20:57,697
Do you want some water?

222
00:20:57,873 --> 00:20:59,807
- Yeah, sure.
- Yeah?

223
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:07,144
You didn't tell me how cute he was.

224
00:21:07,316 --> 00:21:09,443
He's not that cute.
Doesn't talk much either.

225
00:21:09,618 --> 00:21:11,950
I couldn't get anything out of him
except he's a librarian.

226
00:21:12,120 --> 00:21:14,953
Well, maybe if you would stop
interrogating him...

227
00:21:15,123 --> 00:21:18,149
You never had a boyfriend.
You spend every minute with the guy.

228
00:21:18,327 --> 00:21:20,420
- Wondering what the draw is.
- Leave her alone.

229
00:21:20,595 --> 00:21:23,655
She's codependent. You thought
she was gonna dodge that bullet?

230
00:21:23,832 --> 00:21:25,424
I don't know.

231
00:21:25,600 --> 00:21:28,194
I just think he's not that cute.

232
00:21:28,503 --> 00:21:31,700
All right,
so can we put the potatoes in yet?

233
00:21:31,873 --> 00:21:34,967
Or do you wanna wait
until the vegetables are done?

234
00:21:39,715 --> 00:21:42,047
CHARISSE: Where's the pan?
GOMEZ: How do I know?

235
00:21:42,217 --> 00:21:44,481
CHARISSE: You can help.
GOMEZ: I don't even live here.

236
00:21:44,653 --> 00:21:46,280
CHARISSE: You...
GOMEZ: First, I'm a man.

237
00:21:46,455 --> 00:21:47,752
Second of all, I'm a guest here.

238
00:22:23,725 --> 00:22:26,159
Are you reading my diary?

239
00:22:27,329 --> 00:22:30,093
Told you that was private.

240
00:22:32,034 --> 00:22:35,526
- I didn't read it.
- Well, it kind of looked like you did.

241
00:22:36,805 --> 00:22:39,296
I was trying to find the dates.

242
00:22:39,841 --> 00:22:42,071
The dates that I go to see you.

243
00:22:42,611 --> 00:22:46,206
So I could tell the little girl in the meadow.
If I'm that important to her...

244
00:22:46,381 --> 00:22:50,477
...I wanted to tell her when I was coming
to see her so she wouldn't have to wait.

245
00:22:53,121 --> 00:22:56,887
Christ, I'm sorry.
I don't know what I was thinking.

246
00:22:57,392 --> 00:22:59,087
I should go.

247
00:23:04,099 --> 00:23:05,930
I'd like you to stay.

248
00:23:12,507 --> 00:23:14,498
[CROWD MURMURING]

249
00:23:18,680 --> 00:23:19,908
WOMAN:
You were there all night.

250
00:23:20,082 --> 00:23:23,643
MAN 1: Come on, kick his ass.
MAN 2: Guys, check this out.

251
00:23:23,819 --> 00:23:25,810
[MEN YELLING INDISTINCTLY]

252
00:23:28,023 --> 00:23:30,856
MAN 3: Come on, he's a fag. Kick his ass.
MAN 4: Oh, no.

253
00:23:31,026 --> 00:23:32,288
Come on.

254
00:23:32,461 --> 00:23:33,485
[GRUNTING]

255
00:23:36,731 --> 00:23:38,756
Hey, hey, hey. Break it up, break it up.

256
00:23:38,934 --> 00:23:40,196
- Henry.
- Gomez.

257
00:23:40,368 --> 00:23:41,665
What are you doing?

258
00:23:41,870 --> 00:23:43,235
Goddamn homophobe.

259
00:23:43,405 --> 00:23:46,101
Dude, what in the hell are you wearing?

260
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:49,868
- What's the date?
- What do you mean, "what's the date?"

261
00:23:50,045 --> 00:23:52,570
- What year?
- What do you mean, "what year?"

262
00:23:52,747 --> 00:23:57,184
- Forget it. I gotta get some clothes.
- Yeah, the pink's not working for you. Hey.

263
00:23:57,352 --> 00:23:59,684
GOMEZ: What are you doing now?
- Picking a lock.

264
00:23:59,855 --> 00:24:01,880
GOMEZ: Huh?
- Close the door.

265
00:24:04,326 --> 00:24:07,693
You wanna tell me what the hell's
going on here? What are you on?

266
00:24:07,863 --> 00:24:09,387
Seriously.

267
00:24:09,564 --> 00:24:14,160
Hey, you know, if you have a problem,
maybe I can help.

268
00:24:14,336 --> 00:24:16,065
Yeah, right.

269
00:24:16,705 --> 00:24:19,333
I don't give a shit about you,
but Clare I care about.

270
00:24:19,508 --> 00:24:24,343
- Why don't you tell me what this is about?
- You wanna know? I'm gonna tell you.

271
00:24:24,513 --> 00:24:27,141
Because you and I are gonna be friends
for a long time.

272
00:24:27,315 --> 00:24:28,612
You might as well know now.

273
00:24:28,783 --> 00:24:31,718
- Know what?
- I look older, right?

274
00:24:32,854 --> 00:24:34,287
That's because I am.

275
00:24:34,456 --> 00:24:36,856
I've come back to this night
from the future.

276
00:24:37,025 --> 00:24:38,890
I'm a time traveler.

277
00:24:40,328 --> 00:24:43,229
Oh, my God, you are out of your mind.

278
00:24:43,398 --> 00:24:45,263
Started when I was 6 years old.

279
00:24:45,767 --> 00:24:49,669
I have fits. I disappear.
I travel through time.

280
00:24:49,838 --> 00:24:52,272
I've come to this night from 2003.
What year is this?

281
00:24:52,440 --> 00:24:54,840
- 1995. I don't like this.
- I get dislocated in time.

282
00:24:55,010 --> 00:24:57,877
I never know when it's gonna happen
or where I'm gonna end up.

283
00:24:58,046 --> 00:25:01,482
I have to break and enter,
steal clothes from the first person I see.

284
00:25:01,650 --> 00:25:02,810
You name it, I've done it.

285
00:25:02,984 --> 00:25:04,849
Uh-huh.
There's something wrong with you.

286
00:25:05,020 --> 00:25:06,544
Yeah, there is.

287
00:25:06,721 --> 00:25:10,248
But I care about Clare more than you can
imagine, so don't worry about that.

288
00:25:10,425 --> 00:25:12,359
GOMEZ:
Whoa, hey, I'm reassured.

289
00:25:12,527 --> 00:25:15,655
Listen, in the future,
do Charisse and I get married?

290
00:25:15,830 --> 00:25:17,559
Do I go bald? Does Charisse go bald?

291
00:25:17,732 --> 00:25:19,859
I'm not gonna tell you things
about your life.

292
00:25:20,035 --> 00:25:23,937
- Knowing stuff in advance makes you crazy.
- You're full of shit, you know that?

293
00:25:25,140 --> 00:25:27,836
- You won't think that in a minute.
- Yeah? Why's that?

294
00:25:28,877 --> 00:25:30,208
[SIGHS]

295
00:25:36,885 --> 00:25:38,216
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

296
00:25:41,790 --> 00:25:43,417
- Hey.
- Hey.

297
00:25:43,592 --> 00:25:45,890
- Charisse is out.
- Henry here?

298
00:25:46,061 --> 00:25:49,030
- No, he's at the library.
- Don't marry him, Clare.

299
00:25:49,631 --> 00:25:52,657
- What?
- Just don't marry Henry, okay?

300
00:25:53,001 --> 00:25:56,459
- You know, he hasn't asked me yet.
- Yeah, you know what I'm talking about.

301
00:25:58,540 --> 00:26:00,132
I love him.

302
00:26:01,376 --> 00:26:02,673
Here. Come here.

303
00:26:07,682 --> 00:26:10,207
I saw him last night at the Vic.

304
00:26:10,385 --> 00:26:14,253
Barrel of laughs. First, he beats up a guy,
then we burglarize the Army-Navy store.

305
00:26:14,422 --> 00:26:18,825
And then he tells me
that he's a time traveler.

306
00:26:21,229 --> 00:26:24,426
You know,
because he travels through time.

307
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:27,229
And did you believe him?

308
00:26:27,402 --> 00:26:28,733
Um...

309
00:26:29,204 --> 00:26:31,764
Not until he disappeared
right in front of me, you know?

310
00:26:31,940 --> 00:26:33,840
Like, he just disappeared.

311
00:26:34,009 --> 00:26:35,533
Yeah, it's a problem.

312
00:26:40,482 --> 00:26:45,886
- Are you saying you know about this?
- I've known for a very long time.

313
00:26:46,888 --> 00:26:49,482
Okay, I don't know
what the hell's going on, all right?

314
00:26:49,658 --> 00:26:52,855
I don't need to know how the whole thing
works, because I don't care.

315
00:26:53,028 --> 00:26:57,362
But, uh, just presuming for a second that
we're not all out of our fricking minds...

316
00:26:57,532 --> 00:27:00,330
...whatever Henry has, it's, uh...

317
00:27:00,802 --> 00:27:02,599
It's not good.

318
00:27:04,239 --> 00:27:08,073
I've been waiting for him my entire life,
and now he's here.

319
00:27:08,276 --> 00:27:12,076
I mean, it's already happened.
I couldn't even change it if I wanted to.

320
00:27:17,952 --> 00:27:19,442
Well, you're worse off than I thought.

321
00:27:19,621 --> 00:27:20,952
[CLARE CHUCKLES]

322
00:27:22,657 --> 00:27:24,625
Maybe I am.

323
00:27:31,433 --> 00:27:34,766
MAN:
That guy stole my wallet. My wallet!

324
00:27:36,471 --> 00:27:37,802
[SIGHS]

325
00:27:37,972 --> 00:27:42,068
That guy stole my wallet. Hold the train.

326
00:28:04,566 --> 00:28:05,999
Excuse me.

327
00:28:07,702 --> 00:28:10,296
- Are you Annette DeTamble?
- Yes.

328
00:28:11,272 --> 00:28:12,432
I love you.

329
00:28:13,775 --> 00:28:16,573
I mean, your work. Your singing.

330
00:28:16,745 --> 00:28:18,007
You have a great voice.

331
00:28:20,815 --> 00:28:23,113
Thank you. I appreciate that.

332
00:28:23,284 --> 00:28:27,448
People don't usually recognize me.
Not on the subway, anyway. Ha, ha.

333
00:28:27,756 --> 00:28:29,053
My name's Henry.

334
00:28:30,525 --> 00:28:31,651
How funny.

335
00:28:31,826 --> 00:28:35,694
I have a son named Henry.
But he's just 3.

336
00:28:38,633 --> 00:28:39,827
I met a girl.

337
00:28:40,935 --> 00:28:44,166
And since I've been with her, I feel safe.

338
00:28:45,106 --> 00:28:49,338
I haven't felt that way for a long time.
Not since I was a kid.

339
00:28:50,912 --> 00:28:53,142
I wish she could hear you sing.

340
00:28:53,848 --> 00:28:55,873
Maybe she will one day.

341
00:29:04,959 --> 00:29:06,483
I'm really glad I met you.

342
00:29:08,163 --> 00:29:10,188
I'm glad I met you too.

343
00:29:10,799 --> 00:29:12,460
[CHUCKLES]

344
00:29:17,405 --> 00:29:20,499
Make sure that girl knows
how you feel about her.

345
00:29:23,211 --> 00:29:25,509
Your son loves you very much.

346
00:29:27,315 --> 00:29:28,907
I know.

347
00:30:12,227 --> 00:30:13,888
HENRY:
Hello?

348
00:30:16,631 --> 00:30:18,189
Dad?

349
00:30:25,573 --> 00:30:27,803
What are you doing here?

350
00:30:31,846 --> 00:30:33,643
I was worried.

351
00:30:34,249 --> 00:30:35,944
I called you several times.

352
00:30:37,252 --> 00:30:39,743
I've been ill.

353
00:30:40,822 --> 00:30:42,289
Yeah.

354
00:30:43,458 --> 00:30:45,983
- I called the orchestra.
- Hmm.

355
00:30:46,160 --> 00:30:48,685
They told me you've been on sick leave
since September.

356
00:30:48,863 --> 00:30:50,353
August.

357
00:30:56,037 --> 00:30:57,698
Makes it hard to play the violin.

358
00:31:00,408 --> 00:31:02,239
HENRY:
That's not gonna help.

359
00:31:02,977 --> 00:31:04,569
Sure it does.

360
00:31:05,480 --> 00:31:07,345
- Want one?
- No.

361
00:31:07,515 --> 00:31:09,540
I don't drink anymore.

362
00:31:10,351 --> 00:31:12,046
Pity.

363
00:31:12,854 --> 00:31:15,448
It was our one shared enthusiasm.

364
00:31:15,623 --> 00:31:19,024
First thing we gotta do is get someone
in here to clean the place up.

365
00:31:19,193 --> 00:31:21,593
Make you some meals.
I mean, do you even eat?

366
00:31:21,763 --> 00:31:24,755
I mean, do you want me
to come around more often?

367
00:31:24,933 --> 00:31:26,059
Take you to the doctor?

368
00:31:26,234 --> 00:31:28,862
- Help pay some bills? What?
- No.

369
00:31:29,037 --> 00:31:32,006
No? "No" to what, everything?
Or just some of that?

370
00:31:32,173 --> 00:31:36,633
Get your own life in order
before you start telling me how to live mine.

371
00:31:39,013 --> 00:31:40,878
I'm getting married.

372
00:31:43,484 --> 00:31:44,712
Who would marry you?

373
00:31:49,324 --> 00:31:52,725
- Does she know about...?
- She knows everything about me.

374
00:31:52,894 --> 00:31:54,555
Everything.

375
00:31:55,730 --> 00:31:57,527
Her name's Clare.

376
00:31:57,699 --> 00:32:00,497
Clare Abshire. She's an artist.

377
00:32:00,668 --> 00:32:03,569
I'd really like to give her
Mom's wedding and engagement rings.

378
00:32:03,738 --> 00:32:06,866
That's why I'm here.
And I think Mom would really like that.

379
00:32:07,308 --> 00:32:12,041
How would you know what your mother
would like? You barely knew her.

380
00:32:12,213 --> 00:32:13,874
I knew her.

381
00:32:14,349 --> 00:32:15,941
I still know her now.

382
00:32:16,117 --> 00:32:17,846
I've just seen her on the subway.

383
00:32:19,020 --> 00:32:22,615
I see her pushing me in the stroller.
You know, I see her with you too.

384
00:32:22,790 --> 00:32:25,156
This thing I have isn't always a curse.

385
00:32:25,326 --> 00:32:28,227
Then why don't you keep her
from getting into that goddamn car?

386
00:32:28,396 --> 00:32:30,455
I would if I could. You know that.

387
00:32:36,004 --> 00:32:38,871
I've watched her die hundreds of times.

388
00:32:39,040 --> 00:32:41,531
I can never get there in time to change it.

389
00:33:06,734 --> 00:33:08,634
I still miss her.

390
00:33:11,673 --> 00:33:13,163
I miss her every day.

391
00:33:15,043 --> 00:33:16,772
So do I.

392
00:33:57,351 --> 00:33:58,682
[CLARE GROANS SOFTLY]

393
00:34:14,102 --> 00:34:15,831
Henry.

394
00:34:20,608 --> 00:34:26,308
I never wanted to have anything in my life
that I couldn't stand losing.

395
00:34:28,816 --> 00:34:30,681
But it's too late for that.

396
00:34:32,153 --> 00:34:35,816
It's not because you're beautiful
and smart and perfect.

397
00:34:39,794 --> 00:34:41,819
I don't feel alone anymore.

398
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:47,165
Will you marry me?

399
00:34:54,909 --> 00:34:56,501
No.

400
00:34:58,813 --> 00:35:00,644
I didn't mean that.

401
00:35:01,849 --> 00:35:04,181
I just wanted to try it.
I just wanted to say it...

402
00:35:04,352 --> 00:35:07,287
...to assert my own sense
of free will. I...

403
00:35:07,922 --> 00:35:09,787
But my free will wants you.

404
00:35:09,957 --> 00:35:11,754
- So it's a yes?
- Yes.

405
00:35:11,926 --> 00:35:13,416
[LAUGHING]

406
00:35:13,594 --> 00:35:15,789
Of course.

407
00:35:21,002 --> 00:35:23,664
A thousand times yes.

408
00:35:45,326 --> 00:35:47,658
MARK: You ever handled a gun before?
HENRY: Not exactly. L...

409
00:35:47,829 --> 00:35:49,558
- Hello?
- Mom, we're home.

410
00:35:49,730 --> 00:35:51,357
MARK:
You are in for a treat, my friend.

411
00:35:51,532 --> 00:35:55,662
Oh, my God. That dress looks like
it's been through the wars.

412
00:35:55,837 --> 00:35:58,806
- I told you to have it shipped.
- Mom, it'll be fine.

413
00:35:58,973 --> 00:36:01,965
Henry, I don't mean to be a nag,
but any word on your father?

414
00:36:02,143 --> 00:36:04,668
- We'll need to adjust the seating plan.
- I'm not sure he'll make it.

415
00:36:04,846 --> 00:36:05,870
[GUNSHOT]

416
00:36:06,047 --> 00:36:08,572
Shame. He could've joined in
on the killing spree.

417
00:36:08,749 --> 00:36:10,876
It's how men bond, apparently.

418
00:36:11,052 --> 00:36:12,076
- Philip.
PHILIP: Pull.

419
00:36:12,253 --> 00:36:13,982
LUCILLE:
Philip, they're here.

420
00:36:19,627 --> 00:36:23,358
Are you ready for this? It's a real circus.

421
00:36:24,398 --> 00:36:26,161
Yes, I am, sir.

422
00:36:29,804 --> 00:36:33,296
Hope you know what you've signed on for.
With Clare, I mean.

423
00:36:34,275 --> 00:36:35,833
I'm not sure I understand.

424
00:36:37,612 --> 00:36:41,844
Her mother and I didn't succeed in
preparing her for the real world, I'm afraid.

425
00:36:42,283 --> 00:36:43,716
I don't know about that.

426
00:36:43,885 --> 00:36:46,046
She seems to manage pretty well
for herself.

427
00:36:46,220 --> 00:36:49,348
Well, that's good to hear.

428
00:36:52,493 --> 00:36:54,984
Do you ever do any hunting?

429
00:36:57,698 --> 00:36:59,962
No. Never.

430
00:37:01,469 --> 00:37:04,097
Well, maybe I could
take you out sometime.

431
00:37:04,272 --> 00:37:06,604
I'd like that. Yeah.

432
00:37:06,774 --> 00:37:09,174
Usually I'm the one who's getting chased.

433
00:37:11,812 --> 00:37:13,973
You know what they say.

434
00:37:15,182 --> 00:37:17,173
Life's a hunt.

435
00:37:21,789 --> 00:37:23,347
BARBER: Good morning.
HENRY: Morning.

436
00:37:23,524 --> 00:37:25,253
BARBER:
Have a seat.

437
00:37:26,594 --> 00:37:28,687
What can we do for you today?

438
00:37:29,330 --> 00:37:32,163
- Cut it off.
- All of it?

439
00:37:32,333 --> 00:37:36,827
Yeah, I'm getting married tomorrow.
And my wife, she likes short hair.

440
00:37:37,004 --> 00:37:39,097
Congratulations.

441
00:37:39,273 --> 00:37:44,210
See what we can do for you.
Try to make you happy, the both of you.

442
00:37:49,917 --> 00:37:52,147
PORTER: Take your bags?
RICHARD: I've got it. Thank you.

443
00:37:52,320 --> 00:37:53,810
PORTER:
Very well.

444
00:38:03,397 --> 00:38:06,560
Dad. You came.

445
00:38:16,777 --> 00:38:18,369
Well...

446
00:38:19,246 --> 00:38:21,339
...I suppose I'll have to meet her parents.

447
00:38:21,882 --> 00:38:24,009
Her dad's a Republican.

448
00:38:24,185 --> 00:38:25,413
And a hunter.

449
00:38:27,088 --> 00:38:28,715
Oh, dear.

450
00:38:30,024 --> 00:38:31,719
HENRY:
Give us a second. I gotta take a Valium.

451
00:38:31,892 --> 00:38:33,951
Valium? Is that a good idea?

452
00:38:34,128 --> 00:38:36,562
Wouldn't be a wedding without a groom.

453
00:38:36,731 --> 00:38:37,755
Freak.

454
00:38:37,932 --> 00:38:38,956
[METAL CLANGS]

455
00:38:39,133 --> 00:38:40,327
You okay in there?

456
00:38:45,573 --> 00:38:47,336
Oh, shit.

457
00:38:47,508 --> 00:38:50,306
MAN: Let me get this for you, ladies.
WOMAN: Thank you.

458
00:38:50,845 --> 00:38:55,248
- This hair, it's always been difficult.
- Mom. Stop already, okay?

459
00:38:55,416 --> 00:38:56,576
It's fine.

460
00:38:57,385 --> 00:39:00,411
But, my God, you are beautiful.

461
00:39:01,288 --> 00:39:03,279
When Henry sees you
coming down the aisle...

462
00:39:03,457 --> 00:39:05,288
...he's gonna pass out on the spot.

463
00:39:05,459 --> 00:39:07,120
[ALICIA CHUCKLES]

464
00:39:07,828 --> 00:39:09,921
Could you go check on the boys?

465
00:39:10,097 --> 00:39:12,657
Okay. Oh, God.

466
00:39:12,933 --> 00:39:14,195
Okay. Oh, shit.

467
00:39:14,368 --> 00:39:15,699
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

468
00:39:16,103 --> 00:39:19,595
ALICIA: Are you guys nearly ready?
- Yeah. Yeah, we're good. We're fine.

469
00:39:19,774 --> 00:39:23,301
Great day for a wedding, huh?
Flowers look really pretty and everything.

470
00:39:23,477 --> 00:39:26,969
Everyone else is downstairs waiting.
What do you want me to tell Clare?

471
00:39:27,148 --> 00:39:31,016
We'll just probably be, like, another
half an hour or so to get pretty, and then...

472
00:39:31,185 --> 00:39:35,679
And then, you know, put some pants on,
and then we'll be ready to go.

473
00:39:36,390 --> 00:39:37,618
Five minutes.

474
00:39:38,325 --> 00:39:40,520
I'll let Clare know.

475
00:39:41,629 --> 00:39:42,789
GOMEZ:
What year are you from?

476
00:39:42,963 --> 00:39:46,194
- You look like my grandpa.
- Don't worry. It all works out.

477
00:39:46,367 --> 00:39:48,232
Oh, great.

478
00:39:48,602 --> 00:39:52,197
I just hope no one notices the gray hair.
You're not gonna have time to shave.

479
00:39:53,808 --> 00:39:55,901
I don't know where they are.

480
00:40:04,418 --> 00:40:06,409
[VIOLIN PLAYING]

481
00:40:48,829 --> 00:40:50,558
Good luck, darling.

482
00:40:50,998 --> 00:40:53,330
[WHISPERS]
He's got gray hair.

483
00:40:56,871 --> 00:40:58,065
[WHISPERS]
What the hell?

484
00:40:58,239 --> 00:41:00,434
[WHISPERS]
Don't swear. We're getting married.

485
00:41:00,608 --> 00:41:05,272
We are gathered here today to celebrate
the marriage of Henry and Clare.

486
00:41:05,446 --> 00:41:09,940
In the presence of family and friends
and before God, they exchange these vows:

487
00:41:10,117 --> 00:41:11,141
[CHUCKLES]

488
00:41:11,318 --> 00:41:16,051
To have and to hold from this day forward,
for richer or for poorer...

489
00:41:16,223 --> 00:41:20,284
...for better or for worse,
in sickness and in health.

490
00:41:20,461 --> 00:41:22,452
[CROWD MURMURING]

491
00:41:23,597 --> 00:41:26,088
And now I'd like to invite
my lovely daughter...

492
00:41:26,267 --> 00:41:31,933
...and my gallant new son-in-law
to the dance floor.

493
00:41:34,408 --> 00:41:37,400
[BAND PLAYING JO Y DIVISION'S
"LOVE WILL TEAR US APART" SLOWLY]

494
00:42:06,240 --> 00:42:08,367
Howdy, stranger.

495
00:42:10,444 --> 00:42:13,174
Sorry I missed the ceremony.

496
00:42:13,347 --> 00:42:15,508
You didn't.

497
00:42:17,418 --> 00:42:19,716
Do you wish I was him?

498
00:42:22,323 --> 00:42:24,223
But you are.

499
00:42:30,798 --> 00:42:33,790
[SINGING JO Y DIVISION'S
"LOVE WILL TEAR US APART"]

500
00:42:36,070 --> 00:42:38,630
CLARE:
I wonder if I'm a bigamist.

501
00:42:39,006 --> 00:42:42,066
I think you're allowed to marry the same
person as many times as you want.

502
00:42:42,243 --> 00:42:43,574
[CLARE CHUCKLES]

503
00:43:12,506 --> 00:43:15,168
[CLARE LAUGHING]

504
00:43:20,814 --> 00:43:23,374
Oh, no. Don't.

505
00:43:23,550 --> 00:43:24,574
[SCREAMS]

506
00:43:24,752 --> 00:43:26,083
[CLOTHING CRUMPLES]

507
00:43:47,241 --> 00:43:48,572
[SIGHS]

508
00:44:45,299 --> 00:44:46,960
Finally.

509
00:44:47,134 --> 00:44:49,967
- Clare.
- Who'd you expect?

510
00:44:52,539 --> 00:44:56,942
I brought you a turkey leg.
Our cook roasts the best turkey around.

511
00:44:57,378 --> 00:45:00,472
Well, that's what everyone says, anyway.

512
00:45:05,085 --> 00:45:06,950
My dad was saving it for lunch.

513
00:45:08,222 --> 00:45:12,750
He's been ignoring me,
so I really didn't think he deserved it.

514
00:45:14,495 --> 00:45:16,622
He's been ignoring my mom too.

515
00:45:16,797 --> 00:45:21,234
Alicia says they're really gonna
get a divorce this time.

516
00:45:24,204 --> 00:45:25,535
They're not.

517
00:45:27,541 --> 00:45:30,408
You never told me
anything like that before.

518
00:45:30,878 --> 00:45:33,745
Well, I don't want you to worry
if you don't have to.

519
00:45:36,750 --> 00:45:38,513
Maybe they should get a divorce.

520
00:45:39,353 --> 00:45:42,117
Yeah, maybe.

521
00:45:43,791 --> 00:45:45,622
Are you married?

522
00:45:46,927 --> 00:45:48,485
Yes, I am.

523
00:45:49,730 --> 00:45:54,099
- Is your wife a time traveler?
- No. No, thank God.

524
00:45:54,935 --> 00:45:56,596
Do you love her?

525
00:45:57,771 --> 00:46:01,070
Yes. Very much.

526
00:46:05,245 --> 00:46:06,269
What's wrong?

527
00:46:06,447 --> 00:46:11,282
Nothing. I was just hoping
you're married to me.

528
00:46:22,529 --> 00:46:24,724
BETTE DAVIS [ON TV]:
Did you ever think about time?

529
00:46:24,898 --> 00:46:26,525
It goes, Alec.

530
00:46:26,700 --> 00:46:28,895
That's the business of time.

531
00:46:29,069 --> 00:46:31,867
Tick, tick, tick...

532
00:46:42,382 --> 00:46:43,713
[CLARE GROANS SOFTLY]

533
00:46:44,818 --> 00:46:47,252
I was with you in the meadow.

534
00:46:48,222 --> 00:46:50,019
You were?

535
00:46:51,692 --> 00:46:53,455
You were jealous of my wife.

536
00:46:53,627 --> 00:46:54,958
[CLARE CHUCKLES]

537
00:46:56,597 --> 00:46:58,326
I was.

538
00:46:59,700 --> 00:47:03,158
I used to try and convince myself...

539
00:47:03,337 --> 00:47:07,137
...that you were married to someone fat
with a mustache.

540
00:47:07,708 --> 00:47:10,802
Well, that is my type.

541
00:47:11,111 --> 00:47:13,102
[BOTH LAUGH]

542
00:47:22,823 --> 00:47:24,984
CLARE:
Come on, let's do this.

543
00:47:28,095 --> 00:47:30,893
- That's great, guys. Thanks.
- You're welcome.

544
00:47:33,133 --> 00:47:34,691
CLARE:
Honey?

545
00:47:43,043 --> 00:47:44,738
MAN:
Get him, Charlie.

546
00:47:44,912 --> 00:47:46,004
Drop it.

547
00:48:05,899 --> 00:48:07,230
[PLATE BREAKS]

548
00:48:41,668 --> 00:48:44,398
MAN:
Get back here, you son of a bitch.

549
00:48:50,243 --> 00:48:51,267
You're back.

550
00:48:51,878 --> 00:48:53,243
Did I miss Christmas?

551
00:48:53,413 --> 00:48:56,576
Yeah. And New Year's.

552
00:48:58,318 --> 00:49:00,878
Henry, you've been gone two weeks.

553
00:49:01,054 --> 00:49:04,046
I couldn't get back. I tried everything.

554
00:49:04,625 --> 00:49:06,786
Even got drunk trying to trigger it.

555
00:49:06,960 --> 00:49:09,019
Guess that didn't work.

556
00:49:11,898 --> 00:49:14,867
Um, I have to go.

557
00:49:15,035 --> 00:49:17,128
Now? I just got here.

558
00:49:17,304 --> 00:49:21,331
I know, but I have a show in two weeks.
Jeremy gave me a space to work in.

559
00:49:21,508 --> 00:49:25,205
I mean, this place is too small.
I can't work here anymore.

560
00:49:25,379 --> 00:49:28,109
And, Henry, my life doesn't stop
because you're gone.

561
00:49:28,281 --> 00:49:29,612
I never said it did.

562
00:49:33,053 --> 00:49:34,645
- Could we talk about this?
- Talk?

563
00:49:34,821 --> 00:49:37,881
I have been here for two weeks
wanting to talk to you.

564
00:49:38,058 --> 00:49:39,389
What do you wanna talk about?

565
00:49:39,559 --> 00:49:43,325
I mean, how bad it feels to sit here
and wait for you?

566
00:49:45,132 --> 00:49:46,929
I'm going to work.

567
00:49:50,070 --> 00:49:51,401
[SIGHS]

568
00:49:54,207 --> 00:49:56,107
JEREMY:
This is gonna be great. Have no worries.

569
00:49:56,276 --> 00:49:57,834
CLARE:
All right. Thank you, sir.

570
00:49:58,011 --> 00:49:59,478
JEREMY: Good night.
CLARE: Good night.

571
00:49:59,646 --> 00:50:02,137
WOMAN: Yeah, I can't believe that.
MAN: Yeah.

572
00:50:36,983 --> 00:50:40,441
- We'll never make it in time.
- In time for what?

573
00:50:40,620 --> 00:50:44,488
Somewhere in America, moments from now,
there could be a new multimillionaire.

574
00:50:44,658 --> 00:50:47,821
Good evening, everybody. I'm Dave Long.
It's Tuesday...

575
00:50:47,994 --> 00:50:50,622
CLARE: You can't be in here.
HENRY: We have to watch something.

576
00:50:50,797 --> 00:50:53,595
CLARE: The TVs are gonna set you off.
HENRY: We have to watch something.

577
00:50:53,767 --> 00:50:57,863
MAN [ON TV]: To win, all you have to do...
CLARE: What's that?

578
00:50:58,038 --> 00:50:59,505
MAN [ON TV]:
Good luck.

579
00:51:01,942 --> 00:51:03,239
What'd you do?

580
00:51:03,410 --> 00:51:05,139
MAN [ON TV]:
Our first winning number is...

581
00:51:05,312 --> 00:51:08,713
- Seventeen.
MAN [ON TV]: Seventeen.

582
00:51:13,186 --> 00:51:14,847
Up next:

583
00:51:15,021 --> 00:51:18,684
- Maybe a 23.
MAN [ON TV]: Number 23.

584
00:51:19,226 --> 00:51:21,285
Or even a 32.

585
00:51:22,763 --> 00:51:24,890
MAN [ON TV]:
Thirty-two is next.

586
00:51:26,500 --> 00:51:31,267
- Couldn't possibly be a 40.
MAN [ON TV]: Followed by 40.

587
00:51:31,972 --> 00:51:34,532
- That shouldn't be a 12.
MAN [ON TV]: And our last number is...

588
00:51:34,708 --> 00:51:36,733
...a 12.

589
00:51:38,211 --> 00:51:40,771
So here are your winning numbers:

590
00:51:41,448 --> 00:51:48,411
- Seventeen, 23, 32, 40 and 12.
- You just won $5 million.

591
00:51:48,588 --> 00:51:50,215
You can't do that.

592
00:51:50,390 --> 00:51:52,722
It's... It's cheating.

593
00:51:53,126 --> 00:51:57,825
- Okay. Let's rip it up.
- No.

594
00:51:58,799 --> 00:52:02,701
Look, there are a lot of downsides
to my condition, okay?

595
00:52:02,869 --> 00:52:04,359
But this is not one of them.

596
00:52:06,673 --> 00:52:09,699
REALTOR: Exquisite plasterwork
in every room of the house.

597
00:52:09,876 --> 00:52:11,844
Isn't it gorgeous?

598
00:52:13,346 --> 00:52:15,143
This is not it.

599
00:52:16,082 --> 00:52:19,051
- But I like it.
- You'll like another one more.

600
00:52:21,755 --> 00:52:25,486
Just look at the fireplace.
It's got the "wow" factor.

601
00:52:25,659 --> 00:52:28,093
The details, the architecture,
the windows.

602
00:52:28,261 --> 00:52:31,458
- Spectacular.
- No. Not the one.

603
00:52:32,065 --> 00:52:33,896
Uh, thank you.

604
00:52:38,071 --> 00:52:42,872
Just look at this landscaping.
Wouldn't you love to see it in the spring?

605
00:52:43,243 --> 00:52:47,145
Now, it's a little smaller
than the other places, but big on charm.

606
00:52:48,014 --> 00:52:51,609
Now, the main entrance of this house
is actually towards the rear...

607
00:52:51,785 --> 00:52:54,515
...where there is a charming garden.

608
00:52:54,688 --> 00:53:00,217
But look at these features. The fireplace.
That staircase, it's so handsome.

609
00:53:00,393 --> 00:53:03,021
The wide-plank flooring. Love that.

610
00:53:06,666 --> 00:53:08,258
Clare.

611
00:53:10,670 --> 00:53:12,729
- We're home. See the garage?
- Uh-huh.

612
00:53:12,906 --> 00:53:14,168
- That's your studio.
- Aah!

613
00:53:14,341 --> 00:53:15,740
HENRY:
Come on. Come on.

614
00:53:15,909 --> 00:53:17,467
Come on.

615
00:53:20,313 --> 00:53:21,405
CLARE:
So here's the garden.

616
00:53:21,581 --> 00:53:23,242
- And over there is my studio.
CHARISSE: Oh, my.

617
00:53:23,416 --> 00:53:24,747
[GOMEZ WHISTLES]

618
00:53:25,352 --> 00:53:27,479
GOMEZ: Things are going okay.
CHARISSE: This is...

619
00:53:27,654 --> 00:53:28,678
CLARE: Mint?
- Yes.

620
00:53:28,855 --> 00:53:30,152
- And black for you.
GOMEZ: Mm-hm.

621
00:53:30,323 --> 00:53:32,723
- How many more of these do you want?
- Three's good.

622
00:53:32,893 --> 00:53:34,417
CHARISSE:
He's awake.

623
00:53:34,594 --> 00:53:36,892
- He's kicking. Max is kicking.
CLARE: Oh!

624
00:53:39,199 --> 00:53:41,190
[GRUNTING NEARBY]

625
00:53:47,908 --> 00:53:49,239
[COUGHING NEARBY]

626
00:53:53,046 --> 00:53:54,070
[CLARE GASPS]

627
00:54:22,075 --> 00:54:24,475
Do you know when you're gonna die?

628
00:54:32,652 --> 00:54:34,051
No.

629
00:54:36,289 --> 00:54:38,587
I've never seen you older.

630
00:54:40,760 --> 00:54:43,194
I've never seen you older
than 40-something.

631
00:54:43,997 --> 00:54:45,464
Never.

632
00:54:47,667 --> 00:54:49,100
Maybe you stop...

633
00:54:49,269 --> 00:54:51,533
Maybe you stop traveling.

634
00:54:56,376 --> 00:54:58,776
Somebody... Somebody finds a cure.

635
00:54:58,945 --> 00:55:03,109
There's gotta be some kind of drug
you can take. There's gotta be someone...

636
00:55:03,516 --> 00:55:05,711
Something. Something that can help.

637
00:55:14,828 --> 00:55:16,489
We're having a baby.

638
00:55:20,433 --> 00:55:21,730
What?

639
00:55:38,351 --> 00:55:39,841
I...

640
00:55:40,487 --> 00:55:42,717
I think it's time.

641
00:55:43,723 --> 00:55:46,556
It's time you find Dr. Kendrick.

642
00:55:49,462 --> 00:55:51,327
How did you say you found me?

643
00:55:53,033 --> 00:55:54,728
When I'm older...

644
00:55:54,901 --> 00:55:59,099
...I travel back in time to see my wife
when she's a little girl.

645
00:56:00,440 --> 00:56:03,341
She says I mentioned a Dr. Kendrick.

646
00:56:03,510 --> 00:56:08,607
I found three in the Chicago area:
One an ENT, one a podiatrist, so...

647
00:56:08,782 --> 00:56:10,943
I'm a geneticist.

648
00:56:13,053 --> 00:56:15,521
And I have a genetic anomaly.

649
00:56:15,688 --> 00:56:17,315
It's called Chrono-Impairment.

650
00:56:19,559 --> 00:56:24,223
That's a term you came up with, apparently.
That's what she says.

651
00:56:24,564 --> 00:56:27,362
Of course, now I've mentioned it,
you will call it that...

652
00:56:27,534 --> 00:56:30,332
...and it'll be hard to tell
which came first.

653
00:56:31,604 --> 00:56:34,232
You see, that's the thing
about time travel.

654
00:56:38,144 --> 00:56:43,013
Did my students put you up to this?
Because, man, you are good.

655
00:56:43,183 --> 00:56:45,879
Oh, God.

656
00:56:46,986 --> 00:56:48,715
You got me.

657
00:56:54,494 --> 00:56:57,019
I knew this would be a waste of my time.

658
00:56:58,898 --> 00:57:02,891
Wait a minute. Uh, wait. Here.
Henry, wait.

659
00:58:01,361 --> 00:58:02,988
Hey.

660
00:58:11,504 --> 00:58:13,904
I lost the baby.

661
00:58:23,416 --> 00:58:25,407
[CLARE SOBBING]

662
00:58:38,565 --> 00:58:40,032
Kendrick.

663
00:58:42,302 --> 00:58:43,997
Mr. DeTamble.

664
00:58:44,571 --> 00:58:46,505
My wife had a miscarriage.

665
00:58:50,243 --> 00:58:54,646
I am very sorry about that,
but I don't see what I can do to help.

666
00:58:54,814 --> 00:58:57,647
What if the baby's a traveler like me?

667
00:58:58,351 --> 00:59:02,219
What if it has the same genetic anomaly?
What if it traveled out of the womb?

668
00:59:02,655 --> 00:59:06,682
You need help.
Not the kind of help I can give you.

669
00:59:07,160 --> 00:59:09,287
How can I prove it to you?

670
00:59:09,696 --> 00:59:13,393
You can't. It's impossible.

671
00:59:13,766 --> 00:59:15,358
Well, just do one test.

672
00:59:16,536 --> 00:59:21,064
If you don't find anything, fine. I'll leave
you alone, you can go back to your life.

673
00:59:21,507 --> 00:59:23,168
I'm calling Security.

674
00:59:24,611 --> 00:59:26,203
The grant.

675
00:59:26,412 --> 00:59:28,277
The Berger Grant.

676
00:59:31,251 --> 00:59:35,347
- Have you applied for it yet?
- How did you find out about that?

677
00:59:37,390 --> 00:59:38,414
You win.

678
00:59:49,435 --> 00:59:53,428
We're going to start the first series.
It'll take about 10 minutes.

679
00:59:57,844 --> 00:59:59,675
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY ON TV]

680
00:59:59,846 --> 01:00:01,837
[MRI CLUNKING]

681
01:00:17,664 --> 01:00:19,655
[COMPUTER BEEPING]

682
01:00:29,876 --> 01:00:31,935
Oh, shit.

683
01:00:36,549 --> 01:00:41,111
Your brain emits a blast
of electromagnetic energy...

684
01:00:41,287 --> 01:00:45,690
...akin to an epileptic's
right at the moment you travel.

685
01:00:45,858 --> 01:00:48,520
And you can see it right here.

686
01:00:49,095 --> 01:00:51,928
Now, there are drugs for epilepsy
we can use.

687
01:00:52,965 --> 01:00:57,629
But all of these drugs
are way too strong for a fetus...

688
01:00:57,804 --> 01:01:01,296
...if, indeed, it is a similar condition
which is causing the miscarriage.

689
01:01:02,208 --> 01:01:06,338
I'm 10 weeks in now,
and we've never been that far along...

690
01:01:06,512 --> 01:01:08,571
...so maybe the baby isn't gonna travel.

691
01:01:08,748 --> 01:01:10,613
We're going to find out.

692
01:01:10,783 --> 01:01:13,411
We're going to take a look
at Henry's genetic code.

693
01:01:14,053 --> 01:01:17,181
We'd like to take a look
at the clock genes.

694
01:01:17,590 --> 01:01:20,252
And then I would like to run the same test
on the fetus.

695
01:01:21,194 --> 01:01:25,096
Not to worry.
It's a noninvasive extraction of cells.

696
01:01:25,264 --> 01:01:27,459
But perhaps we'll get
some sort of indication...

697
01:01:27,633 --> 01:01:30,193
...as how to bring you to full term.

698
01:01:50,923 --> 01:01:52,356
Honey.

699
01:01:52,792 --> 01:01:54,817
- What?
- Wake up. You're bleeding.

700
01:01:54,994 --> 01:01:56,018
[GASPS]

701
01:01:56,195 --> 01:01:57,457
What?

702
01:02:08,741 --> 01:02:10,641
HENRY:
We could adopt.

703
01:02:14,447 --> 01:02:19,475
What's wrong with me wanting
one normal thing in my life?

704
01:02:19,652 --> 01:02:24,680
I wanna be a mother.
I wanna bear a child, your child.

705
01:02:24,857 --> 01:02:27,121
Why can't I have that?

706
01:02:28,227 --> 01:02:32,095
I've never seen us with a baby. Never.
I've traveled to the future...

707
01:02:32,265 --> 01:02:34,756
...and I've never seen it.
- I don't wanna hear that.

708
01:02:34,934 --> 01:02:38,165
- You heard what the doctor said. You'd be...
- Stop.

709
01:02:49,549 --> 01:02:51,107
Okay, Henry.

710
01:02:51,284 --> 01:02:54,981
Uh, just to be official about this,
I need to ask you one last time:

711
01:02:55,154 --> 01:02:59,454
- You're sure you wanna do this?
- Yeah, yeah. I've signed the papers.

712
01:02:59,625 --> 01:03:03,721
Yeah. Yeah, I know, but, uh, vasectomy's
rarely a one-party decision.

713
01:03:04,630 --> 01:03:06,894
Yeah, well, this time it is.

714
01:03:07,700 --> 01:03:08,962
NURSE:
You all right?

715
01:03:09,135 --> 01:03:10,659
- You need us to call someone?
- No.

716
01:03:10,837 --> 01:03:12,168
NURSE:
A cab?

717
01:03:16,375 --> 01:03:18,036
[CLOTHING CRUMPLES]

718
01:03:25,852 --> 01:03:27,479
CLARE:
Henry.

719
01:03:33,893 --> 01:03:36,589
Hey. What's the matter?

720
01:03:36,796 --> 01:03:39,594
I don't really feel like being here
right now.

721
01:03:44,904 --> 01:03:46,633
Is it me?

722
01:03:47,006 --> 01:03:48,496
No.

723
01:03:49,775 --> 01:03:51,538
I did something.

724
01:03:52,578 --> 01:03:54,978
It was hard, and you won't like it.

725
01:03:56,649 --> 01:03:58,344
What'd you do?

726
01:03:58,518 --> 01:04:00,349
You won't like it.

727
01:04:01,153 --> 01:04:03,212
Well, then why'd you do it?

728
01:04:04,423 --> 01:04:07,620
- To stop us from fighting.
- We're fighting?

729
01:04:08,261 --> 01:04:10,058
Why?

730
01:04:12,198 --> 01:04:14,962
Well, just once, one time, could you...?

731
01:04:15,134 --> 01:04:18,661
Could you tell me the answer
to something I'm asking you?

732
01:04:19,672 --> 01:04:21,503
You wouldn't get it anyway.

733
01:04:24,710 --> 01:04:26,701
[CLARE GRUNTS]

734
01:04:28,381 --> 01:04:30,815
That wasn't very nice.

735
01:04:35,154 --> 01:04:37,019
You've never kissed me before.

736
01:05:57,436 --> 01:05:58,801
I was with you in the meadow.

737
01:06:04,110 --> 01:06:07,102
- When?
- You looked about 18.

738
01:06:08,280 --> 01:06:10,214
It was our first kiss.

739
01:06:13,586 --> 01:06:14,917
Hmm...

740
01:06:16,689 --> 01:06:18,418
You were having a bad day.

